+In 1486, hostilities broke out between the Mamluks and the [[Ottoman Empire]] in a battle for control over western Asia, and the Ottomans captured Palestine in 1516.{{sfn|Krämer|2011|page=40}} Between the mid-16th and 17th centuries, a close-knit alliance of three local dynasties, the [[Ridwan dynasty|Ridwans]] of [[Gaza City|Gaza]], the [[Al-Lajjun#Early rule and the Tarabay family|Turabay]]s of [[al-Lajjun]] and the Farrukhs of [[Nablus]], governed Palestine on behalf of the central Ottoman authorities.{{sfn|Zeevi|1996|page=45}} 

 In the 18th century, the [[al-Zayadina|Zaydani]] clan under the leadership of the Arab sheikh [[Daher el-Omar]] ruled large parts of Palestine autonomously{{sfn|Phillipp|2013|pages=42-43}} until the Ottomans were able to defeat him and his family in their [[Galilee]] strongholds in 1775-76.{{sfn|Joudah|1987|pages=115-117}} Daher had turned the port of [[Acre, Israel|Acre]] into a major power fueled in part by monopolization of the trade of [[cotton]] and [[olive oil]] from Palestine to Europe. Acre's dominance in the southern Levant increased further under Daher's successor [[Jezzar Pasha]] at the expense of its traditional power center in [[Damascus]].{{sfn|Burns|2005|page=246}}

