 Israel is located in the [[Southern Levant]], a region known historically as [[Canaan]], the [[Land of Israel]], [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] and the [[Holy Land]]. In antiquity, it was home to several [[Israelites|Israelite]] and [[Jews|Jewish]] kingdoms, including [[Israel and Judah]] and [[Hasmonean dynasty|Hasmonean Judea]]. Over the ages, the region was ruled by imperial powers such as the [[Neo-Assyrian Empire|Assyrians]], [[Neo-Babylonian Empire|Babylonians]], [[Achaemenid Empire|Persians]], [[Hellenistic period|Greeks]], and [[Roman Empire|Romans]]. During Roman rule, Jews became a minority in Palestine. The region later came under [[Byzantine]] and [[Arab conquest of the Levant|Arab rule]]. In the medieval period, it was part of the [[Islamic caliphates]], the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem|Crusader Kingdom of Jerusalem]], and the [[Ottoman Empire]]. The late 19th century saw the rise of [[Zionism]], a movement advocating for the establishment of a [[Homeland for the Jewish people|Jewish homeland]], during which the [[Jewish land purchase in Palestine|Jewish people began purchasing land in Palestine]]. Under the [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]] by the [[League of Nations]] after World War I, [[Aliyah|Jewish immigration]] to the region increased considerably, leading to [[Intercommunal conflict in Mandatory Palestine|tensions between Jews and the Arab majority population]]. The UN-approved [[United Nations Partition Plan for Palestine|1947 partition plan]] triggered [[1947–1948 civil war in Mandatory Palestine|a civil war]] between these two peoples. The British terminated the Mandate on 14 May 1948, and Israel [[Israeli Declaration of Independence|declared independence]] on the same day.
